for 2019; </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>RECORD DATE </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Only stockholders of record at the
close of business on March&nbsp;4, 2019 are entitled to vote. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>ANNUAL REPORT </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Annual Report to stockholders for fiscal year 2018 is enclosed if you received proxy materials by mail and is accessible on the Internet at <U>www.proxyvote.com</U>
if you received the Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy Materials or previously consented to electronic delivery of proxy materials. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV ALIGN="right">

meeting, you must be a holder of Illinois Tool Works Inc. shares as of the record date of March&nbsp;4, 2019, and obtain a registration confirmation (&#147;Ticket&#148;) in advance. Tickets can be printed by accessing Shareholder Meeting
Registration at <I><U>www.proxyvote.com</U></I><I> </I>and following the instructions provided. You will need the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16-digit</FONT> control number that is printed in the box marked by the arrow&nbsp;<FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#224;</FONT></FONT> included on your proxy card or Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy Materials. Tickets will be available to registered and beneficial owners and to one
guest accompanying each registered and beneficial owner. <B>You must bring your ticket to the meeting to gain access. Requests for admission tickets will be processed in the order in which they are received. Please note that seating is limited and
requests for tickets will be accepted on a first-come, first-served basis.</B> </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>*Enter the campus from 150 Waukegan Road at Overlook Drive. Signage will direct
you to the meeting location. </B></P>

Availability of Proxy Materials, or <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">E-Proxy</FONT> Notice, in hand when you call or go to the proxy vote website. If you hold your shares through a bank or broker that does not offer telephone or Internet voting,
please complete and return your proxy card by mail. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2%; margin-right:2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Whether or not you plan to attend the meeting, please vote as soon as
possible. Under New</B><B></B><B>&nbsp;York Stock Exchange rules, your broker will NOT be able to vote your shares on Proposals 1, 3, 4 or 5 unless they receive specific instructions from you.</B> If you hold your shares through a bank or brokerage
account, we strongly encourage you to return the voting instruction card to your bank, broker or other holder of record so that your vote is counted. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; padding-bottom:12pt; margin-left:2%; margin-right:2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Avoid escheatment. </B>We have been advised that some states are strictly enforcing unclaimed property laws and
requiring shares held in &#147;inactive&#148; accounts to be escheated to the state in which the stockholder was last known to reside.<B> One way you can show that your account is active is to vote your shares.</B> </P></div>

Annual Report to Stockholders, including the Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K,</FONT> and this 2019 Proxy Statement are available on the Company&#146;s website at <U>www.itw.com</U> under the &#147;Investor Relations&#148;
link. Paper copies are available without charge upon written request to the Company&#146;s address above, Attention: Secretary. </B></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_5"></A>Proposal 1 - Election of Directors </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Stockholders are being asked to elect the eleven directors named in this proxy statement at our Annual Meeting. The individuals listed below have been nominated by the
Board of Directors as recommended by the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee. See &#147;Corporate Governance Policies and Practices&#148; for more information regarding our candidate selection process. Each director will serve until the
May 2020 Annual Meeting, until a qualified successor director has been elected, or until he or she resigns or is removed. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We will vote your shares as you specify on
the proxy card, by telephone, by Internet or by mail. If you do not specify how you want your shares voted, we will vote them &#147;FOR&#148; the election of all the nominees listed below. If unforeseen circumstances (such as death or disability)
make it necessary for the Board of Directors to substitute another person for any of the nominees, we will vote your shares &#147;FOR&#148; that other person. The Board of Directors does not anticipate that any nominee will be unable to serve. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Each nominee for director brings a strong and unique background and set of skills to the Board, giving the Board as a whole competence and experience in a variety of
areas. Set forth below is biographical information provided by the nominees, as well as a description of the experiences, qualifications, skills and attributes that led the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee and the Board to conclude that
each nominee should serve as a director of the Company. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="91%"></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt">


<IMG SRC="g587187g56p82.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
</P> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Daniel J. Brutto</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Retired President of</P> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">UPS International</P>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">and Senior Vice</P> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">President of United</P>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Parcel Service, Inc.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Director since: 2012</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom:1pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Age: 62</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Brutto retired as President of UPS International and Senior Vice
President of United Parcel Service, Inc., a global package delivery, supply chain management and freight forwarding company, having served in these capacities from 2008 to 2013. From 2016 to 2017, he served as Executive Chairman of Radial, Inc., a
global fulfillment, customer care and omnichannel technology company; from 2015 to 2016 he served as Vice Chairman of eBay Enterprise/Innotrac, the predecessor business to Radial, and prior to 2015 he served as a director of Innotrac.
Mr.&nbsp;Brutto had over 38 years of experience at UPS, serving in various areas with increasing levels of responsibility, including global operations, finance, accounting, information systems, mergers&nbsp;&amp; acquisitions, marketing and business
development. His service at UPS included President, Global Freight Forwarding and corporate controller. He has served as a director of ITW since 2012 and currently serves as a director of Sysco Corporation. He has not served as a director of any
other publicly traded company in the last five years. In the past he has served on the board of the US China Business Council, the Guangdong Economic Council and the Turkey Economic Advisory Council. He was also a delegate to the World Economic
Forum, Davos Switzerland, from 2009 to 2013.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Skills and
Qualifications:</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Brutto&#146;s significant strategic, operational, and
financial leadership experience with a major global company, including the establishment of operations in 35 countries, along with his significant international business experience, bring valuable perspectives to our Board.</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">3 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_6"></A>Board of Directors and Its Committees </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company&#146;s Board of Directors met five times during
2018. In addition to these Board meetings, directors attended meetings of Board committees. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-employee</FONT> directors, all of whom are independent, met five times in regularly scheduled executive sessions in
conjunction with regular Board meetings. The Company strongly encourages its directors to attend all Board and committee meetings and the Annual Meeting of Stockholders. In 2018, all of the directors attended 100% of the meetings of the Board and
the committees on which they serve and the Annual Meeting of Stockholders. See &#147;Corporate Governance Highlights &#151; Director Nominees&#148; for more information about meeting attendance. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Role of Chairman and CEO </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Pursuant to the
Company&#146;s Corporate Governance Guidelines, the Board examines whether the role of chairman and chief executive officer should be combined each time the Board elects a new CEO, and may determine to separate or combine the offices of chairman and
CEO at such other times as it deems appropriate. E. Scott Santi was elected President and CEO in November 2012, and the Board decided to separate the roles of CEO and Chairman at that time. Given Mr.&nbsp;Santi&#146;s successful transition into the
CEO role and his deep knowledge and understanding of the Company&#146;s business model, operations and culture, the Board determined that he is best positioned to lead the Board in its ongoing oversight of the Company&#146;s operations and strategy.
In May 2015, the Board elected Mr.&nbsp;Santi Chairman of the Board and CEO. The Board continues to believe that Mr.&nbsp;Santi is best positioned to lead the Board, given his demonstrated success and quality of leadership. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Strong Independent Lead Director </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Since
the roles of Chairman and CEO were combined in 2015, the Board has elected a strong independent director as Lead Director. James A. Skinner has served as the independent Lead Director of the Board since May 2017. The Board believes that this
structure, which calls for a strong, independent and highly experienced lead director with well-defined responsibilities, along with the Company&#146;s experienced and engaged independent directors, provides effective oversight of the Company&#146;s
management. In conjunction with the Board&#146;s role in overall strategy and succession planning as described below, our lead director actively engages with our Chairman/CEO on such matters. In addition, the Corporate Governance Guidelines state
that the lead director will: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="9%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">preside at all meetings of the Board at which the chairman is not present, including executive sessions of the independent
directors; </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">act as a key liaison between the chairman and the independent directors; </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">approve meeting agendas, schedules and information sent to the Board; </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board of Directors has standing audit, compensation, corporate governance and nominating, finance, and executive committees. Under the terms of the respective
charters, each member of the audit, compensation, and corporate governance and nominating committees must meet applicable New York Stock Exchange (&#147;NYSE&#148;) and Securities and Exchange Commission (&#147;SEC&#148;) independence requirements.
</P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">9 </P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Board&#146;s Role in Company Strategy and Executive Succession Planning
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board has an active role in the Company&#146;s overall strategies. Each year, the Board conducts a comprehensive,
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">in-depth</FONT> review of the Company&#146;s long-term strategy and annual operating plan and actively monitors and reviews management&#146;s progress in executing both throughout the year. The Board also conducts an
annual review of the Company&#146;s corporate governance practices. In addition, throughout the year the Board conducts individual segment strategy reviews with segment leadership. The Board also periodically reviews the Company&#146;s Corporate
Social Responsibility (CSR) strategy. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board recognizes that one of its most important duties is to ensure continuity in the Company&#146;s senior leadership by
overseeing the development of executive talent and planning for the effective succession of the Company&#146;s CEO and the executive leadership team. In order to ensure that the succession planning and leadership development process supports and
enhances ITW&#146;s strategic objectives, the Board regularly consults with the CEO on the Company&#146;s organizational needs, its leadership pipeline and the succession plans for critical leadership positions. On an annual basis, the Board also
conducts a detailed review of executive succession plans, in addition to addressing the Company&#146;s talent management initiatives and discussing individuals who are considered potential future senior executives of the Company. Similarly,
leadership development, including succession planning, is a top priority of the CEO and the senior executive team. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Board&#146;s Role in
Risk Oversight </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board of Directors is responsible for the overall risk oversight of the Company. The Board has delegated to the Audit Committee
the responsibility to review and evaluate the Company&#146;s overall financial and compliance risk policies and practices, including certain environmental, safety and health matters and related policies, has delegated to the Finance Committee the
responsibility for the review and evaluation of risks relating to financings, capital structure and other treasury functions, and has delegated to the Compensation Committee the responsibility for the review and evaluation of risks arising from the
Company&#146;s compensation policies and practices. The Compensation Committee also advises management on whether the Company&#146;s compensation policies and practices may have a material adverse effect on the Company. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company has identified key business risks of the Company, including, but not limited to, legal/compliance/reputation, controllership/tax, key leader
continuity/succession, supply chain integrity/continuity, data security risks and risk of recession and significant external events. The Board has a formal process for continuous review of such risks. Certain risks are reviewed and discussed at
least annually, while others are considered on a rotating basis. Company management routinely presents on these risks at meetings of the Company&#146;s Board and Board committees, providing them with an opportunity to discuss the risks and the
Company&#146;s risk mitigation processes. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In instances where a particular committee reviews certain risks, that committee reports on those risks to the full Board
on a regular basis. The Company believes that because each of these committees is comprised solely of independent directors, the Chairman and CEO of the Company is subject to the risk oversight of independent directors. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The committee descriptions below provide more detail regarding the risk oversight delegated to each committee by the Board. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit Committee </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee is
responsible for the integrity of the Company&#146;s financial statements, compliance with legal and regulatory requirements, the independence and performance of ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm, and the performance of the
Company&#146;s internal audit function. In addition, the Committee is responsible for the engagement of our independent registered public </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">10 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
accounting firm and assists the Board with respect to matters involving and overseeing accounting, financial reporting and internal audit functions. In addition, as required by the Company&#146;s
Corporate Governance Guidelines and Audit Committee charter, the Audit Committee annually reviews legal affairs and environmental, safety and health matters that may have a material impact on the Company&#146;s financial statements or the
Company&#146;s compliance policies. Finally, the Audit Committee, as requested by the Board of Directors, reviews and evaluates certain of our policies and practices with respect to risk assessment and risk management and steps taken by management
to monitor and control such exposures. Additional information on the Audit Committee and its activities is set forth under &#147;Audit Committee Report&#148; below. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Compensation Committee </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation
Committee establishes and oversees the Company&#146;s executive compensation philosophy, programs and policies, including ensuring that executive compensation is aligned with Company and individual performance. The Compensation Committee recommends
to the other independent directors compensation for the chief executive officer, reviews and approves the chief executive officer&#146;s recommendations regarding the compensation of our other executive officers, and makes recommendations regarding
new incentive compensation and equity-based plans or amendments to any existing plans. The Compensation Committee also is responsible for reviewing and evaluating risks arising from our compensation policies and practices and providing input to
management on whether such policies and practices may have a material adverse effect on the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Under its charter, the Compensation Committee may retain an
independent compensation consultant or other advisors. The Compensation Committee engaged Frederic W. Cook&nbsp;&amp; Co., Inc. (&#147;Cook&#148;), an independent consultant, as its independent advisor to review the Company&#146;s overall executive
compensation program, review the peer group of companies used by the Compensation Committee for comparison purposes and assess our compensation governance process. Based on representations from Cook and executive officers and directors of the
Company, the Compensation Committee has determined that Cook and its individual compensation advisor to the committee are independent. See &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis &#151; How We Make Compensation Decisions &#151; Role of the
Compensation Consultant.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Additional information on the Compensation Committee, its activities, its relationship with its compensation consultant and the role
of management in setting compensation is provided under &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; below. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Corporate Governance and
Nominating Committee </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee identifies, evaluates and recommends director candidates; develops,
administers and recommends corporate governance guidelines; oversees the evaluations of the performance and procedures of the Board and individual directors; makes recommendations as to Board committees and Board size; and makes a recommendation to
the Board regarding the Board&#146;s determination of director independence for the Board, the Audit Committee and the Compensation Committee. It is also responsible for identifying qualification criteria for Board members. This committee also
oversees and makes recommendations to the independent directors regarding <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> director compensation. See &#147;Corporate Governance Policies and Practices &#151; Director Candidate Selection
Process&#148; below for a description of the director selection process. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Finance Committee </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Finance Committee reviews, evaluates and recommends management&#146;s proposals to the Board relating to the Company&#146;s financings and dividend policy, and
reviews and evaluates an annual summary of the funding and investment status of significant benefit plans sponsored by the Company </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">11 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
globally. The Finance Committee also periodically reviews and evaluates the Company&#146;s capital structure and capital allocation strategy as well as risks arising from the Company&#146;s
treasury function. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Executive Committee </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Executive Committee may act on behalf of the Board if a matter requires Board action between meetings of the full Board. The Executive Committee&#146;s authority in
certain matters is limited by law and our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws.</FONT> </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Committee Memberships </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the current committee memberships and the number of meetings held by each committee during 2018. </P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_7"></A>Corporate Governance Policies and Practices </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>General </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">One of our core values is integrity, and we have long believed that good corporate governance is important to assure that the Company is managed for the long-term
benefit of its stockholders. Accordingly, we continuously review our corporate governance policies and practices not only for compliance with applicable law, the rules and regulations of the SEC, and the listing standards of the NYSE, but also for
good corporate governance and social responsibility principles and standards of behavior. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Our Corporate Governance Guidelines provide a framework for the effective governance of the Company and address such
matters as Board structure and Board governance and the responsibilities of the independent Lead Director. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Our Statement of Principles of Conduct sets forth standards of conduct applicable to all employees and directors.
</P></TD></TR></TABLE>

our products to assure that they are from conflict free sources if they originate within the Democratic Republic of Congo or its adjoining countries. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

of Principles of Conduct in all relevant respects and specifically requires adherence to laws against child labor, forced labor, wage and working hours, discrimination, environmental, health&nbsp;&amp; safety and fair dealing. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Our Supplier Expectations inform our suppliers that they are expected to focus on reducing their environmental impact, give
back to their communities, and support sourcing to minority or women-owned business <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">sub-suppliers.</FONT> </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The
Audit, Compensation and Corporate Governance and Nominating Committees each review their Committee charters annually and recommend that the Board of Directors approve any changes. Our website includes the charters of these committees, the
Company&#146;s Corporate Governance Guidelines, the Statement of Principles of Conduct (our code of business conduct and ethics for directors, officers and employees), the Global Anti-Corruption Policy, the Code of Ethics for the Chief Executive
Officer and key financial and accounting personnel, our Corporate Social Responsibility reports, Modern Slavery and Human Trafficking Statement, Conflict Minerals Policy, Supplier Code of Conduct and Supplier Expectations. In addition, we will
promptly post any amendments to or waivers of the Code of Ethics on our website. You can find this and other corporate governance information at <B><U>www.itw.com</U></B>. We also will provide copies of this information upon request. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Board Independence </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Corporate
Governance and Nominating Committee conducts an annual review and makes a recommendation to the full Board as to whether each of our directors meets the applicable independence standards of the NYSE. In accordance with the NYSE listing standards,
our Board of Directors has adopted categorical standards for director independence, including heightened standards applicable to members of our Audit and Compensation Committees. A copy of the Company&#146;s Categorical Standards for Director
Independence is attached as <B>Appendix A</B>. A director will not be </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">13 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
considered independent unless the Board of Directors determines that the director has no material relationship with the Company (directly, or as a partner, stockholder or officer of an
organization that has a material relationship with the Company). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board has determined that each of the current directors, except E. Scott Santi, has no material
relationship with the Company other than as a director and is independent within the meaning of the Company&#146;s Categorical Standards for Director Independence and the listing standards of the NYSE. In making its independence determinations, the
Board of Directors has broadly considered all relevant facts and circumstances including that: (1)&nbsp;Ms.&nbsp;Crown and Messrs. Henderson and&nbsp;Smith serve as directors of Northern Trust Corporation and its subsidiary, The Northern Trust
Company, with which the Company has a commercial banking relationship as described under &#147;Certain Relationships and Related Party Transactions&#148; below; (2)&nbsp;Messrs. Brutto, Griffith, Henderson, Lenny, Skinner and Ms.&nbsp;Strobel serve
as directors of companies that have an existing customer or supplier relationship with the Company; (3)&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;David&nbsp;B. Smith, Jr. is the nephew of Harold B. Smith, emeritus director of the Company; and (4)&nbsp;each of Messrs. Warren
and Williams are officers of companies with which we conduct business. The Board has concluded that these relationships are not material and, therefore, do not impair the independence of these directors. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Board Evaluations </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board of Directors
and the Audit, Compensation, and Corporate Governance and Nominating Committees conduct annual self-evaluations that assess the effectiveness, processes, skills, functions and other matters relevant to the Board as a whole or to the particular
committee. Results of the evaluations are summarized and discussed at Board and committee meetings. In addition, the Board conducts a peer review evaluation whereby each Board member evaluates the contributions of the other Board members, and each
director receives a summary of the results of the peer review regarding himself or herself. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Director Qualifications and Succession
Planning </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee periodically reviews the skills, experience and characteristics required of Board members
in the context of the current <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">make-up</FONT> of the Board and screens and recommends nominees for director to the full Board. Its assessment includes the skills of Board candidates, such as an understanding of
technologies pertinent to the Company&#146;s businesses, manufacturing, marketing, finance, regulation and public policy, international background and experience, age, diversity and ability to provide strategic insight and direction on the
Company&#146;s key strategic initiatives. In addition to skills and experience, Board candidates are considered based upon various criteria, such as their personal integrity and judgment, global business and social perspective, and concern for the
long-term interests of our stockholders. Although there is no specific policy regarding Board diversity, racial, ethnic and gender diversity are important factors considered in the director selection process. Of the eleven director nominees, two are
female and two are African-American men. In addition, directors must have time available to devote to Board activities and to enhance their knowledge of the global manufacturing environment. Accordingly, we seek to attract and retain a diverse board
composed of highly qualified directors who have sufficient time to attend to their duties and responsibilities to the Company. After receiving recommendations for nominations from the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee, the Board
nominates or elects candidates for director. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Pursuant to ITW&#146;s Corporate Governance Guidelines, a director may not stand for
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">re-election</FONT> after his or her 75th birthday, except in rare circumstances approved by the Board. The Committee believes it is important to replace skills that would be lost as directors approach retirement age
and to identify skills to supplement existing board experience. The Committee discusses with the full Board its analysis of the characteristics and key attributes for future Board candidates. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">14 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Director Candidate Selection Process </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee, or other members of the Board of Directors, may identify a need to add new members to the Board of Directors with
specific skills or to fill a vacancy on the Board. At that time, the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee would initiate a search, seeking input from Board members and senior management and, to the extent it deems appropriate, engaging a
search firm. An initial qualified candidate or a slate of qualified candidates would be identified and presented to the Committee for its evaluation and approval. The Committee would then seek full Board approval of the selected candidate(s). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> permit any stockholder or group of up to 20 stockholders meeting our continuous ownership requirement of 3% or more
of our common stock for at least 3 years to nominate a candidate or candidates for election and require us to include such nominees in our proxy statement and form of proxy. All such proxy access nominations must be accompanied by information about
the nominating stockholders as well as the nominees and meet the requirements as specified in Article II, Section&nbsp;12 of the Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws.</FONT> For a description of the process for submitting a
director candidate through the use of proxy access, see &#147;Other Information &#151; Submitting Proxy Proposals and Director Nominations for the 2020 Annual Meeting &#151; How do I use proxy access to nominate a director candidate to be included
in ITW&#146;s 2020 Proxy Statement?&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> also permit stockholders to nominate directors for consideration at an
annual meeting of stockholders without requiring that their nominees be included in our proxy statement and form of proxy. The policy of the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee is to consider such nominations as are properly submitted
pursuant to Article II, Section&nbsp;10 of the Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws.</FONT> Assuming that a properly submitted stockholder recommendation for a director candidate has been received, the Corporate Governance and
Nominating Committee will evaluate that candidate by following substantially the same process, and applying substantially the same criteria, as for candidates submitted by other sources, but the Committee has no obligation to recommend that
candidate for nomination. For a description of the process for submitting a director candidate without proxy access, see &#147;Other Information &#151; Submitting Proxy Proposals and Director Nominations for the 2020 Annual Meeting &#151; How do I
nominate a director candidate who would not be included in ITW&#146;s Proxy Statement?&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Director Election </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> provide for the election of directors in uncontested elections by majority vote. Under this majority vote standard,
each director must be elected by a majority of the votes cast with respect to that director. For this purpose, a majority of the votes cast means that the number of shares voted &#147;for&#148; a director exceeds the number of shares voted
&#147;against&#148; that director. In a contested election, directors will be elected by a plurality of the votes represented in person or by proxy at the meeting. An election is contested if the number of nominees exceeds the number of directors to
be elected. Whether an election is contested or not is determined ten days in advance of when we file our definitive proxy statement with the SEC. This year&#146;s election is uncontested, and the majority vote standard will apply. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If a nominee who is serving as a director is not elected at an annual meeting, Delaware law provides that the director would continue to serve on the Board as a
&#147;holdover director&#148; until his or her successor is elected. Our Corporate Governance Guidelines, however, require any nominee for director who fails to receive a majority of the votes cast for his or her election to tender his or her
resignation. The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee of the Board will consider the resignation and recommend to the Board whether to accept or reject it. In considering the resignation, the Committee will take into account such factors as
any stated reasons why stockholders voted against the election of the director, the length of service and qualifications of the director, the director&#146;s contributions to the Company, and our Corporate Governance Guidelines. The Board will
consider the </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">15 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
Committee&#146;s recommendation, but no director who failed to receive a majority of the votes cast will participate. We will disclose the results of the Committee&#146;s review within 90 days of
such annual meeting. At our 2018 Annual Meeting, each director received a majority of the votes cast for his or her election. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_8">
</A>Shareholder Engagement </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Shareholder Outreach Activities </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We believe regular, proactive communications with our shareholders to be in the long-term best
interests of the Company. Our investor communications and outreach include annual investor day meetings, investor conferences and quarterly conference calls. These calls are open to the public and are available live and as archived webcasts on our
website. Additionally, we annually reach out to our largest shareholders to obtain feedback on corporate governance matters. In 2019, we invited holders of approximately 53% of our shares, represented by 26 investors, to engage with us. Fourteen
investors, holding in the aggregate approximately 40% of our shares, accepted our invitation. Our engagement topics included the Company&#146;s business model, strategy and performance, our strong governance profile and diverse board, the
shareholder proposal to permit shareholder action by written consent and the shareholder proposal to adopt time-bound, Company-wide greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions targets consistent with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement. We held meaningful
discussions with our investors on these topics. Overall, the discussions were very positive, with investors expressing support for the Company&#146;s governance practices. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">A majority of the investors who engaged with us informed us that they do not support or are leaning against support for the granting of written consent rights to
shareholders, particularly when there is a right to call special meetings, which our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> provide. Similarly, a majority of these investors either do not support the GHG emissions proposal or are inclined
not to support it. These holders generally expressed the view that the GHG proposal is too prescriptive and that management and the Board are in the best position to determine the Company&#146;s corporate social responsibility strategy. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We share feedback from these engagements with our Board. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How to Communicate with Our Directors </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Shareholders and other interested parties may communicate with any of our directors, including our independent Lead Director, or with the independent directors as a
group by sending an <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">e-mail</FONT> to <B><U>independentdirectors@itw.com</U></B> or by writing to the independent directors as a group or to any of our directors c/o Illinois Tool Works Inc., 155 Harlem Avenue,
Glenview, IL 60025, Attention: Secretary, with a designation on the outside of the envelope as a &#147;Board Communication.&#148; Relevant communications will be forwarded by the Secretary to the appropriate directors depending on the facts and
circumstances outlined in the communication. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_9"></A>Director Compensation </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our directors receive retainer-only compensation with no fees
for attending meetings, which is an expected part of Board service. Our committee chairs and Lead Director receive additional retainers for their service in these capacities, and all Board members receive an annual equity grant based on a
fixed-value amount with immediate vesting that avoids entrenchment. Our directors&#146; compensation is compared to that of the same peer group of companies used for executive compensation comparisons.
</P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">16 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee oversees and makes recommendations to the Board regarding <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> director compensation based on
comparisons of financial performance and median compensation levels of our peer group. Peer group directors&#146; compensation data is prepared by Frederic W. Cook&nbsp;&amp; Co., Inc., the independent compensation consulting firm that advises the
Compensation Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Annual Fees </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> director compensation for 2018. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-employee</FONT>
directors were given the opportunity to elect to receive all or a portion of their annual cash retainer, including chair fees, in an equivalent value of ITW common stock pursuant to our 2015 Long-Term Incentive Plan. The number of ITW shares to be
issued to a director is determined by dividing the dollar amount of the fee subject to the election by the fair market value of ITW common stock on the date the fee otherwise would have been paid in cash. </P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Directors&#146; Deferred Fee Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-employee</FONT> directors can defer receipt of all or a portion of their annual cash retainer, including chair/lead director fees,
and/or stock grant until retirement or resignation. Deferred cash amounts are credited with interest quarterly at 120% of the applicable federal long-term rate for the quarter. Cash fees may be deferred as cash or ITW common stock. If a director
elects to defer receipt of any ITW common stock to be received in lieu of a cash payment and/or any portion of his or her stock grant, the deferred shares are credited as stock units to an account in the director&#146;s name. The account receives
share-equivalent credit for cash dividends and is adjusted for stock dividends, splits, combinations or other changes in ITW common stock upon retirement, resignation or a corporate change (as defined in our 2015 Long-Term Incentive Plan), with any
fractional shares paid in cash. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>ITW Common Stock Grant </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company grants stock to its <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> directors under our 2015 Long-Term Incentive Plan, which links this element of
compensation to long-term performance. Under our director compensation program, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> directors serving in 2018 received an annual stock grant equivalent in value to approximately $145,000. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">17 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Director Compensation in Fiscal Year 2018 </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table summarizes the compensation for our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> directors who served during 2018. </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>

<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_10"></A>Ownership of ITW Stock </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Directors and Executive Officers
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the amount of ITW common stock beneficially owned by each director, each named executive officer, and all directors and
executive officers as a group as of December&nbsp;31, 2018, except as otherwise noted. The &#147;named executive officers&#148; as shown in the table are our Chief Executive Officer, our Chief Financial Officer, and the next three most
highly-compensated executive officers who were serving at the end of the last fiscal year (based on total compensation, less the increase in pension value and nonqualified deferred compensation earnings). The &#147;percent of class&#148; calculation
is based on 328,094,747 shares of ITW common stock outstanding as of December&nbsp;31, 2018. Beneficial ownership is a technical term broadly defined by the SEC to mean more than ownership in the usual sense. In general, beneficial ownership
includes any shares a director or executive officer can vote or transfer and stock options and restricted stock units that are currently vested or that become vested within 60 days. Except as otherwise noted, the stockholders named in this table
have sole voting and investment power for all shares shown as beneficially owned by them. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">18 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The number of the directors&#146; phantom stock units disclosed in the table represents an equivalent number of shares
of ITW common stock as of December&nbsp;31, 2018. Because the granting of phantom stock units was discontinued in May 2012, Messrs.&nbsp;Henderson and Lenny, who joined the Board after that date, were not awarded phantom stock units upon joining the
Board. Phantom stock units are not transferable and have no voting rights. The units are payable in cash and are not included in the &#147;percent of class&#148; calculation. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Securities Exchange
Act of 1934 requires that the Company&#146;s executive officers, directors and greater than 10% stockholders file reports of ownership and changes of ownership of ITW common stock with the SEC and the NYSE. Based on a review of copies of these
reports provided to us during fiscal 2018 and written representations from executive officers and directors, we believe that all filing requirements were timely met during 2018. </P>

<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company is providing its Annual Report and its Annual
Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> to stockholders who receive this proxy statement. The Company will provide copies of these reports to brokers, dealers, banks, voting trustees and their nominees for the benefit of their
beneficial owners of record. Additional copies of this proxy statement, the Annual Report and the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2018 are available
without charge upon written request to Illinois Tool Works Inc., 155 Harlem Avenue, Glenview, IL, 60025, Attention: Secretary. You may also review the Company&#146;s SEC filings by visiting the Company&#146;s website at <B><U>www.itw.com</U></B>.

<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>ITW Delivered Another Year of
Strong Performance in 2018 </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">2018 was another year of solid execution and strong performance for ITW. We delivered earnings per share, operating
income, and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">after-tax</FONT> return on invested capital results that were all at the highest levels in the history of the Company. Successful execution of ITW&#146;s long-term strategy and the strength of the highly
differentiated ITW Business Model continue to be the primary drivers of ITW&#146;s financial performance. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company delivered strong earnings growth, with
earnings per share of $7.60, up 15 percent* from 2017, and achieved the following key performance metrics in 2018: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Record operating income of $3.6&nbsp;billion (up six percent)* </P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Throughout this period, the CEO&#146;s compensation has been closely aligned to the Company&#146;s cumulative TSR
performance. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>ITW <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">5-Year</FONT> CEO Pay Versus Cumulative TSR* </I></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g587187g97w95.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:3%; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Note: Mr.&nbsp;Santi was named Chief Executive Office in November, 2012. His compensation totals above are based upon
his total compensation as reported in the Summary Compensation Table, except that his option award amount is valued using ISS&#146; methodology. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">*</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Assumes $100 invested on 12/31/2013 in ITW stock, including reinvestment of dividends. Fiscal years ended December 31.
</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Each element of the Company&#146;s compensation structure plays an integral role in motivating our executives to maximize ITW&#146;s long-term
performance potential. Importantly, more than 75&nbsp;percent of the CEO&#146;s compensation is tied to ITW&#146;s successful achievement of its long-term performance objectives. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">During the first five years of the enterprise strategy through 2017, we made significant progress in achieving our key performance goals set in connection with the
strategy&#146;s implementation. In December 2018, the Company updated these goals for its performance through 2023. The performance objectives of our executive compensation plans, annual and long-term, are closely aligned with these goals. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>ITW&#146;s 2023 Annual Performance Targets </I></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g587187g00c91.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Alignment of Executive Incentives with ITW&#146;s Strategy </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Board of Directors and Compensation Committee are responsible for aligning executive incentives with the Company&#146;s strategy and the best interests of our
stockholders. The Board believes that the Company has a strong track record of thoughtful and diligent governance and execution with respect to aligning executive incentives, as evidenced by the consistently favorable outcome of the annual advisory
stockholder vote on executive compensation (95.9&nbsp;percent favorable in 2016, 97.2&nbsp;percent favorable in 2017 and 95.5&nbsp;percent favorable in 2018). </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">25 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Since the initiation of our current strategy in 2012, the Committee has regularly reviewed incentive plan performance
metrics, both annual and long-term, to ensure ongoing alignment with the strategy&#146;s performance objectives. In the earlier years of the strategy, when we focused on the divestiture of our commoditized businesses and the restructuring of our
businesses, EPS growth was a significant portion of overall incentive compensation. In 2016, as we shifted our focus to organic revenue growth, EPS was removed as a performance metric in the annual incentive plan, while organic revenue growth became
a substantive annual performance measure. Beginning in 2017, we increased options to 50&nbsp;percent of the long-term incentive award value. The other 50&nbsp;percent of the award is tied to the average three-year performance of operating margin,
after-tax ROIC and EPS growth, payable half in cash and half in stock. Also, the three-year performance goals set in 2017 for after-tax ROIC and EPS growth are based on a fixed tax rate to avoid any tax rate benefit from new U.S. tax legislation. We
believe that these performance metrics and the design of the executive incentive plans continue to support the achievement of the current phase of our strategy and, as such, we are not making any plan design changes in short-term or long-term
executive incentives for 2019. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the percent of average incentive pay for our corporate NEOs tied to each of the financial metrics in our
annual and long-term incentive plans for 2018, which remains unchanged from 2017: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Compensation Philosophy
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="92%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TD WIDTH="33%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="65%"></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt" BGCOLOR="#00416a">
<TD HEIGHT="5" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD HEIGHT="5" COLSPAN="2" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#00416a" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" NOWRAP STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Philosophy</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Key Components</FONT></B></FONT></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" ROWSPAN="3" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt" BGCOLOR="#d8d8d8"> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our executive compensation philosophy is designed to deliver competitive total compensation upon the achievement of our strategy objectives, which will attract, motivate
and retain leaders who drive the creation of long-term stockholder value.</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt"> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Target total compensation is based on the median of our peer group and relevant external market data. Actual compensation is determined by achievement of results based
on our goals aligned with ITW&#146;s strategy.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Individual executive compensation is then established
based on an executive&#146;s scope of responsibility, impact on profitable growth, individual performance and breadth of experience.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt"> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pay-for-performance</FONT></FONT> through short- and long-term incentives links compensation to Company
and business segment performance. This <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;pay-at-risk&#148;</FONT></FONT> aligns executive and stockholder interests to help ensure the short- and long-term growth of ITW.</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">26 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Compensation Objectives </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We emphasize a total compensation approach in establishing individual executive compensation levels with each element of compensation serving a specific purpose. In
addition to paying a competitive base salary, we use a mix of different performance-based elements of compensation that reward different aspects of both Company and individual performance. Our 2018 executive compensation program consisted primarily
of three compensation elements: fixed (base salary), variable (annual cash incentives and long-term incentive compensation, including stock options, performance share units and performance cash awards), and retirement and <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> benefits, as illustrated below: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>2018
Compensation Elements </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt" ALIGN="center">

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF"><B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Form&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:1pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" BGCOLOR="#00416a" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt" BGCOLOR="#00416a">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF"><B>Objective</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:1pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt">
<TD VALIGN="middle" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt"><FONT STYLE="font-size:10pt"><B>FIXED</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" ALIGN="center">Base Salary</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000">Cash</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt"> <P STYLE="font-size:1pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL">Market competitive
pay levels to attract and retain highly qualified leaders</P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL">Reflective of individual performance,
experience and scope of responsibility</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt">
<TD VALIGN="middle" ROWSPAN="4" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt"><FONT STYLE="font-size:10pt"><B>VARIABLE</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">Annual&nbsp;Executive</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">Incentive Plan</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">(&#147;EIP&#148;)</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">Cash</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt">Motivate executives to achieve annual Company and business segment performance goals</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:9pt">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For the 2018 EIP, the performance measures for corporate executives were based solely on Company results. For
operating executives, the measures were based 50&nbsp;percent on Company performance and 50&nbsp;percent on the performance of their respective segment. The payout range for the EIP was zero to 200&nbsp;percent of target. For the 2018-2020 PSU and
Performance Cash Awards for both corporate and operating executives, the measures were based solely on Company performance. The payout range for these awards is zero to 200&nbsp;percent. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>2018 Target Compensation </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our total target
compensation (base salary, EIP and long-term incentives) is intended to create a strong correlation between the executive&#146;s compensation and Company and/or business segment performance. The compensation elements based on Company or business
segment performance include EIP, Performance Cash, and equity incentives. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Ninety-one</FONT> percent of 2018 total compensation for the CEO is tied to performance, with 58&nbsp;percent in the form of equity and
33&nbsp;percent in cash awards. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Eighty-one</FONT> percent of 2018 total compensation for the other NEOs (on average) is tied to performance, with 48&nbsp;percent delivered through equity awards and 33&nbsp;percent in
the form of cash awards. Our equity and long-term cash awards have multi-year vesting schedules to align the interests of our executive officers with the long-term interests of our stockholders. The following charts illustrate the allocation of our
total target compensation opportunity for 2018 between fixed (base salary), equity (options and PSUs) and variable (EIP and long-term incentives) components. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Allocation of 2018 Total Target Compensation* </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="84%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Ongoing Best Practices </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We regularly review and refine our executive compensation program to ensure that it continues to address practices and policies that are aligned with our <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pay-for-performance</FONT></FONT> philosophy and the interests of our stockholders. In this regard, our 2018 compensation program reflects the following: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">
