<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; line-height:14pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">5.0%</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; line-height:14pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">10.0%</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt" BGCOLOR="#d8d8d8">
<P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; line-height:14pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">At least 70</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" BGCOLOR="#d8d8d8" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" BGCOLOR="#d8d8d8"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; line-height:14pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">6.0%</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" BGCOLOR="#d8d8d8" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" BGCOLOR="#d8d8d8">
<P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; line-height:14pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">11.7%</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(1)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">For 2018, the Social Security Wage Base was $128,400. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The ECRIP features include a maximum limit on the amount of interest under the Moody&#146;s Rate that would be recognized (12&nbsp;percent annualized, or
15.6&nbsp;percent for amounts eligible to receive 130&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate), a return of deferral feature whereby an individual could elect to receive a return of the principal amount deferred after a period of at least five years,
and options for payment following death, disability or retirement as a lump sum or in monthly installments over 2 to 20 years. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Retirement under the ECRIP is defined
as having attained age 55 with at least 10 years of service, or age 65 with at least 5 years of service. If an ECRIP participant&#146;s employment ends due to retirement, death, or disability, amounts deferred to the ECRIP prior to January&nbsp;1,
2010 will receive interest crediting of 130&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate. Amounts deferred to the ECRIP after December&nbsp;31, 2009 are only eligible to receive 100&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate. During 2018, the Moody&#146;s Rate
applied to ECRIP accounts ranged from 3.88&nbsp;percent to 4.33&nbsp;percent for amounts eligible for 100&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate, and 5.05&nbsp;percent to 5.62&nbsp;percent for amounts eligible for 130&nbsp;percent of Moody&#146;s.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If terminated in conjunction with a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> participants would receive
their ECRIP as <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">a&nbsp;lump-sum</FONT> payment. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table sets forth ECRIP account information for each NEO during fiscal
year 2018. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; line-height:12pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right">$905,889</P></TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; line-height:12pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL">&nbsp;</P></TD>

<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt">
<P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; line-height:12pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL">Steven L. Martindale *</P></TD>

<P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_26"></A>P<A NAME="tx587187_17"></A>otential Payments upon Termination </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Payments and benefits received by NEOs upon termination are
governed by the arrangements described below and quantified at the end of this section. We have estimated the amounts involved assuming that the termination became effective as of December&nbsp;31, 2018, the last business day of fiscal year 2018.
The actual amounts to be paid out can only be determined at the time of the NEOs&#146; departure from the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">No payments or benefits are automatically
payable to NEOs upon a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> and if there is a qualifying termination following a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> there are no tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up</FONT> payments. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">47 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Annual Executive Incentive Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Executive Incentive Plan (&#147;EIP&#148;) provides that if a participant is employed as of the last day of the fiscal year, he or she would receive any amounts
earned under the Executive Incentive Plan for that fiscal year. In the event an NEO becomes permanently disabled or dies, the NEO would be eligible for a possible payout under the Executive Incentive Plan. If termination of employment other than for
death, disability, retirement or <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> occurs prior to the last day of the fiscal year, a participant forfeits his or her award; however, the Compensation
Committee has the discretion to award an amount prorated for the portion of the fiscal year that the participant was employed. Actual amounts earned based on performance by the NEOs in 2018 are discussed in more detail above in &#147;Compensation
Discussion and Analysis &#151; Components of the 2018 Executive Compensation Program &#151; Annual Executive Incentive Plan.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>ITW
Retirement Accumulation Plan and Nonqualified Pension Plan </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">NEOs who are terminated for any reason receive their benefits under the ITW Retirement
Accumulation Plan and Nonqualified Pension Plan as described in the Pension Benefits table above. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Executive Contributory Retirement
Income Plan </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">NEOs who are terminated for any reason receive contributions and accumulated earnings as outlined in the Nonqualified Deferred
Compensation section above. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Long-Term Incentive Plan Awards </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Stock Options and PRSUs: In the event of a termination upon death or disability, all unvested options and PRSUs held by the NEOs would immediately vest. In the event of
a termination upon retirement, unvested PRSUs awarded more than one year prior to retirement would immediately vest, and unvested options and PRSUs awarded within one year prior to retirement would become 25&nbsp;percent vested, with PRSU payouts
subject to achievement of performance metrics. Retirement is defined as a combined age and service of 70, subject to a minimum age of 55 and a minimum service of 5 years. Unvested options will continue to vest according to the original vesting
schedule instead of immediately vesting in the event of a recipient&#146;s retirement more than one year after the grant date of the award. Messrs.&nbsp;Santi, Nagarajan and Martindale meet the retirement criteria for the 2016, 2017 and 2018 awards
as of December&nbsp;31, 2018. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In the event of a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> options and 2016
PRSUs and 2017 PSUs that are continued or replaced would only vest upon a termination of employment after the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control.</FONT></FONT> Unvested options and PRSUs/PSUs that are
not replaced would fully vest. In the case of PRSUs and PSUs, all such vesting events are subject to the achievement of performance goals. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">2016 LTI Cash/2017 and
2018 PSUs and Performance Cash: In the event of a termination upon death or disability, the awards would vest based on the actual performance level achieved and be paid after the end of the performance period. In the event of a termination upon
retirement (defined as a combined age and service of 70, subject to a minimum age of 55 and a minimum service of 5 years), the awards would vest <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rata</FONT> and be paid after the end of the performance period. In
the event of a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> an award that is not replaced will vest <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rata</FONT> at the greater of target or actual achievement
level. In the event of an actual or constructive termination following a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> an award that has been replaced would vest
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rata</FONT> and be paid at the target level (or actual achievement level if greater). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For all NEOs, in the event of a
termination other than upon retirement, death, disability or a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> any unvested options, PRSUs, PSUs, Performance Cash and LTI Cash held on such date by
the NEOs would be forfeited. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">48 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Severance Policy </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company&#146;s 2011 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Severance Compensation Policy provides that,
upon an actual or constructive termination following a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> of the Company, the NEOs and other elected officers would be entitled to receive: (i)&nbsp;two
times annual cash compensation (base salary plus average annual incentive pay over the prior three years); (ii)&nbsp;a prorated amount of that year&#146;s annual incentive bonus at the target level (or actual achievement level if greater); and
(iii)&nbsp;a prorated amount of the value of any LTI Cash or Performance Cash awards at the target level (or actual achievement level if greater). We do not gross up any of the compensation paid in the event of termination due to a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control.</FONT></FONT> </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">49 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Vesting is limited to the extent that the performance level for the award is achieved. If the minimum performance level
is not achieved, the award is forfeited. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(5)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Awards that are replaced after a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> do not receive accelerated vesting. Double-trigger vesting occurs for awards that are continued or replaced if actual or constructive termination
occurs within two years of a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> of the Company. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(6)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pro-rata</FONT> vesting is at the greater of target or actual achievement level.
</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_28"></A>Termination and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Payments and Benefits </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the value of payments and benefits that the NEOs would receive pursuant to the 2011 Long-Term Incentive Plan, the 2015 Long-Term Incentive Plan
and the 2011 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-In-Control</FONT></FONT> Severance Compensation Policy upon retirement, involuntary termination without cause, death, disability or a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> assuming that termination occurred as of the last business day of fiscal 2018. It also shows the Company&#146;s severance benefits that would be payable to
the NEOs and that are available to employees generally. For purposes of this table, LTI Cash and Performance Cash payments are assumed at target level. The value of unvested stock options, if accelerated upon a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> or termination, is&nbsp;determined using the excess, if any, of $126.69 (the closing price of ITW common stock on December&nbsp;31, 2018) over the option exercise price. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Messrs.&nbsp;Santi, O&#146;Herlihy, Nagarajan and Martindale met the retirement criteria for various grants under the Long-Term Incentive Plan during 2018. The 2016
PRSUs, 2017 and 2018 PSUs, Performance Cash and LTI Cash awards vest and are payable after the performance goals have been met. The unvested stock options continue vesting. In addition, 75&nbsp;percent of the 2018 stock option awards would be
forfeited since the assumed retirement occurs within the award year. The PSUs, LTI Cash and Performance Cash awards would be <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rated</FONT> based on the retirement date. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Voluntary termination without good reason is not shown in the table because such a termination would not trigger the payment of severance benefits or annual long-term
incentives. Stock options, PRSUs, PSUs and LTI Cash awards and Performance Cash awards, whether vested or unvested, are subject to forfeiture if the holder competes with, or divulges confidential information about, the Company, or if the
Compensation Committee determines that the holder engaged in gross misconduct or conduct that is against the business interests of the Company. Awards granted after January&nbsp;1, 2011 are also subject to forfeiture, in whole or in part, in order
to comply with applicable law, regulation, stock exchange, accounting rule, or our clawback policy. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_31"></A>Pay Ratio </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As required by Section&nbsp;953(b) of the Dodd-Frank Wall
Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act, and Item 402(u) of Regulation <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K,</FONT> we are providing the following information about the ratio of the annual total compensation of the median ITW employee to the
annual total compensation of our CEO. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The pay ratio reported below, in our view, is a reasonable estimate calculated in a manner consistent with SEC rules, and is
based on the methodologies and assumptions described below. SEC rules identifying the median employee and determining the pay ratio permit companies to employ a wide range of methodologies, estimates and assumptions. As a result, the pay ratio
reported by other companies, which may have utilized other permitted methodologies or assumptions, and which may have a significantly different workforce structure from ours, are likely not comparable to our CEO pay ratio. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company has an extensive global footprint in 55 countries and approximately 48,000 employees as of December&nbsp;31, 2018, of which approximately <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">two-thirds</FONT> are outside of the U.S. While compensation and benefits practices in these countries vary considerably, we commit to providing market competitive compensation and benefits, maintain fair labor practices
and ensure work environments that reflect our core values and culture everywhere we operate. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In 25 countries, ITW has small employee populations. We therefore chose
to apply the de minimis exemption, as permitted by the SEC, and excluded countries which, in the aggregate, make up approximately 4% of our total workforce. The countries excluded are as follows: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="70%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="5%"></TD>
<TD></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#00416a" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B>Countries</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B>Excluded Employees</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT
 COLOR="#ffffff"><B>(in each country)</B></FONT></P></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt">Austria, Estonia, Indonesia, Luxembourg, Peru, Turkey</TD>

<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt">Chile, Columbia, Croatia, Finland, Guatemala, Hong Kong, Norway, Philippines, Puerto Rico, Singapore, South Africa, Switzerland, United Arab
Emirates</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" NOWRAP ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">Less&nbsp;than&nbsp;100&nbsp;employees</TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">To calculate the pay ratio, we identified the median employee based on our employee population as of October&nbsp;31, 2017, which was
approximately 50,000 employees, before excluding approximately 2,000 employees by applying the exemption noted above. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">54 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">To identify the median employee, we collected employees&#146; regular pay (salary or hourly wages), overtime pay and
shift differentials/premiums, and pay received for paid time off. For employees who participate in a company-sponsored defined contribution retirement plan, we also included their company-paid contribution. We did not include annual incentives or
bonuses, sales incentives or commissions, long-term cash or equity incentives, allowances, or any benefits received as part of a company-sponsored defined benefit pension plan. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">With the information collected, we identified 20 employees whose compensation we believed to be around the median of all employees, and we then identified the actual
annual total compensation for each of these employees in order to determine the final median employee compensation. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The ITW employee, who we identified in 2017 as
the median employee, terminated employment with the Company in 2018. As such, we have reviewed the remaining employees in the median group and selected a new median employee. In addition, for 2018, we also included the individual cost of health and
welfare benefits paid by the Company in the annual total compensation since this is also a significant element of the compensation and benefits offerings extended to our employees. We included this amount for both our median employee and our CEO.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our median employee compensation is $49,632. As set forth in the Summary Compensation Table, the total compensation plus the Company costs to provide benefits for
our CEO for 2018 is $17,723,369. Accordingly, the pay ratio between our CEO and median employee is 357:1. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">55 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_32"></A>Certain Relationships and Related Party
Transactions </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We review related-party transactions in accordance with our Statement of Principles of Conduct,
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> and Corporate Governance Guidelines, rather than a separate written policy. A related-party transaction is a transaction involving the Company and any of the following persons: a director, director
nominee or executive officer of the Company; a holder of more than 5% of ITW common stock; or an immediate family member or person sharing the household of any of these persons. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Statement of Principles of Conduct states that our directors, officers and employees must avoid engaging in any activity, such as related-party transactions, that
might create a conflict of interest or a perception of a conflict of interest. These individuals are required to raise for consideration any proposed or actual transaction that they believe may create a conflict of interest. Our <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> provide that no related-party transaction is void or voidable solely because a director has an interest if (1)&nbsp;the material facts are disclosed to or known by the Board of Directors and the transaction
is approved by the disinterested directors or an appropriate Board committee comprised of disinterested directors, (2)&nbsp;the material facts are disclosed to or known by the stockholders and the transaction is approved by the stockholders, or
(3)&nbsp;the transaction is fair to the Company as of the time it is approved. Our Corporate Governance Guidelines provide that the Board will apply established Categorical Standards for Director Independence in making its independence
determinations. Under the standards, certain relationships between the Company and a director would preclude a director from being considered independent. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">On an
annual basis, each director and executive officer completes a Directors&#146; and Officers&#146; Questionnaire, which requires disclosure of any transactions with the Company in which he or she, or any member of his or her immediate family, has a
direct or indirect material interest. The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee reviews the results of these questionnaires and discusses any related-party transaction disclosed therein. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In addition, under its charter, the Audit Committee is responsible for reviewing, approving, ratifying or disapproving all proposed related-party transactions that, if
entered into, would be required to be disclosed under the rules and regulations of the SEC. In reviewing related-party transactions, the Audit Committee considers the factors set forth in our Statement of Principles of Conduct, <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> and Corporate Governance Guidelines, as well as other factors, including the Company&#146;s rationale for entering into the transaction, alternatives to the transaction, whether the transaction is on terms
at least as fair to the Company as would be the case were the transaction entered into with a third party, and the potential for an actual or apparent conflict of interest. No member of the Audit Committee having an interest in a related-party
transaction may participate in any decision regarding that transaction. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We maintain a commercial banking relationship with The Northern Trust Company and its wholly
owned subsidiaries. The Northern Trust Company is a wholly owned subsidiary of Northern Trust Corporation and beneficially owns approximately 6.1% of our common stock. Ms.&nbsp;Susan Crown and Messrs. Jay L. Henderson and David&nbsp;B. Smith, Jr.,
directors of the Company, are also directors of Northern Trust Corporation and The Northern Trust Company. In 2018, The Northern Trust Company provided the following services to the Company: credit services, treasury and investment management
services, trade services, credit enhancement or payment guaranty, acting as agent or fiduciary, consulting services, risk management services, securities lending services and broker dealer services. In addition, The Northern Trust Company serves as
the trustee under the Company&#146;s principal U.S. pension plans. The banking and trustee relationships with The Northern Trust Company are conducted in the ordinary course of business on an <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">arm&#146;s-length</FONT>
basis. Banking, investment management, trustee and other administrative fees paid to The Northern Trust Company or affiliates by the Company were approximately $3.8&nbsp;million in 2018. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">56 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_33"></A>Audit Committee Report </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee of the Board of Directors is composed of five independent directors, as defined in the listing standards of the New York Stock Exchange, and the
Board of Directors has determined that all Audit Committee members are &#147;financially literate.&#148; In addition, the Board of Directors has determined that Messrs.&nbsp;Brutto and Henderson meet the Securities and Exchange Commission criteria
of &#147;audit committee financial expert.&#148; The Audit Committee operates under a written charter adopted by the Board of Directors, which was most recently reviewed by the Audit Committee in February 2019. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee is responsible for providing oversight to the Company&#146;s financial reporting process through periodic meetings with ITW&#146;s independent
registered public accountants, internal auditors and management in order to review accounting, auditing, internal control and financial reporting matters. The Audit Committee is also responsible for assisting the Board in overseeing: (a)&nbsp;the
integrity of the Company&#146;s financial statements; (b)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s compliance with legal and regulatory requirements; (c)&nbsp;the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s qualifications, independence and performance;
(d)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s overall risk policies and practices; and (e)&nbsp;the performance of the Company&#146;s internal audit function. Company management is responsible for the preparation and integrity of the financial reporting information
and related systems of internal controls. The Audit Committee, in carrying out its role, relies on Company senior management, including senior financial management, and ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following is the report of the Audit Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed
with senior management the audited financial statements of the Company. Management has confirmed to the Audit Committee that the financial statements have been prepared in conformity with generally accepted accounting principles. We have also
reviewed and discussed with Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP, ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm, its audit and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s financial statements. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed with senior management their assertion and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s internal controls. Management has confirmed to the Audit
Committee that internal controls over financial reporting have been appropriately designed and are operating effectively to prevent or detect any material financial statement misstatements. We have also reviewed and discussed with
Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP its audit and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s internal controls. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed with Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche
LLP the matters required to be discussed by PCAOB Auditing Standard No.&nbsp;1301 (Communications with Audit Committees) under which Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP must provide us with additional information regarding the scope and results of its
audit of the Company&#146;s financial statements. This information includes: (1)&nbsp;Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP&#146;s responsibility under generally accepted auditing standards; (2)&nbsp;significant accounting policies; (3)&nbsp;management
judgments and estimates; (4)&nbsp;any significant audit adjustments or internal control matters; (5)&nbsp;any disagreements with management; and (6)&nbsp;any difficulties encountered in performing the audit. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have received from Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP a letter providing the disclosures required by applicable requirements of the Public Company Accounting Oversight
Board regarding the independent accountant&#146;s communications with the Audit Committee concerning independence with respect to any relationships between Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP and the Company that in its professional judgment may
reasonably be thought to bear on independence. Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP has discussed its independence with us, and it has confirmed in the letter that, in its professional judgment, it is in a position to serve the Company as its Independent
Registered Public Accounting Firm. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee also discussed with the Company&#146;s internal auditors and independent registered public accounting firm
the overall scope and plans for their respective audits. The Audit Committee meets periodically with the internal auditors and independent registered public accounting firm, with </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">57 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_34"></A>Proposal 2 - Ratification of the Appointment of
Independent </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Registered Public Accounting Firm </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee is directly responsible for the appointment, compensation, retention and oversight of the independent registered public accounting firm retained to
audit ITW&#146;s financial statements. The Audit Committee is also directly involved in the selection of the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s lead engagement partner in conjunction with the mandatory rotation of the lead
engagement partner. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee has engaged Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP (&#147;Deloitte&#148;) to serve as ITW&#146;s independent registered public
accounting firm for the fiscal year ending December&nbsp;31, 2019. Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP has been employed to perform this function for the Company since 2002. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Deloitte, the member firms of
Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, and their respective affiliates (collectively, the &#147;Deloitte Entities&#148;) will bill us approximately $9,764,000 for professional services in connection with the 2018 audit, as compared with $10,450,000 for the 2017
audit of the annual financial statements and internal controls. These fees relate to: (i)&nbsp;the audit of the annual financial statements included in our Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K;</FONT> (ii)&nbsp;the review of
the quarterly financial statements included in our Quarterly Reports on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-Q;</FONT> (iii)&nbsp;the internal controls audit; and (iv)&nbsp;statutory audits. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit-Related Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">During 2018 and 2017,
the Deloitte Entities billed us approximately $98,000 and $54,000, respectively, for audit-related services. These fees relate to work performed with respect to technical accounting assistance. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Tax Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">These fees include work
performed by the Deloitte Entities for 2018 and 2017 with respect to tax compliance services such as assistance in preparing various types of tax returns globally ($1,599,000 and $1,476,000, respectively) and tax planning services, often related to
our restructurings and new tax rules ($601,000 and $677,000, respectively). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>All Other Fees </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">There were no fees for other services rendered by the Deloitte Entities for 2018 and 2017. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit Committee <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pre-Approval</FONT> Policies </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee has adopted policies and procedures for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval</FONT> of all audit and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> related work to be performed by ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm. As a part of those procedures, the Audit Committee performs a qualitative analysis of all <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> work to be performed by our independent registered public accounting firm. Each year, the Audit Committee receives a detailed list of the types of audit-related and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> related services to be performed, along with estimated fee amounts. The Audit Committee then reviews and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approves</FONT> audit work and certain categories of tax
and other <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services that may be performed. In conducting its analysis, the Audit Committee carefully contemplates the nature of the services to be provided and considers whether such services:
(i)&nbsp;are prohibited under applicable rules; (ii)&nbsp;would result in our accountants auditing their own work; (iii)&nbsp;would result in our accountants performing management functions; (iv)&nbsp;would place our accountants in a position of
acting as an advocate for the Company; or (v)&nbsp;would present a real risk of a conflict of interest or otherwise impair our accountants&#146; independence. The Audit Committee also annually <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approves</FONT> the
budget for annual GAAP, statutory and benefit </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">59 </P>

</DIV></Center>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_35"></A>Proposal 3 - Advisory Vote on Executive
Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In accordance with the recommendation by the Board and the preference expressed by our stockholders at the 2017 Annual Meeting, the Company
has an advisory vote on executive compensation annually. The Company is seeking your advisory vote on our executive compensation, as disclosed in the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; section, the compensation tables and any related
material disclosed in this proxy statement pursuant to the SEC&#146;s compensation disclosure rules. The Compensation Committee will review the voting results and take them into consideration when making future decisions regarding executive
compensation, but because your vote is advisory, it will not be binding on the Compensation Committee, the Board or the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We believe that our executive
compensation program is competitive and strongly aligned with our strategic performance goals and the long-term interests of our stockholders. Our compensation program and structure are more fully described in the &#147;Compensation Discussion and
Analysis&#148; and &#147;NEO Compensation&#148; sections of this proxy statement. We encourage you to closely review this information before voting on the compensation we paid to our NEOs in 2018. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We ask our stockholders to approve, on an advisory basis, the compensation of our NEOs by voting &#147;FOR&#148; the following resolution: </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:13%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Resolved, </B>that the compensation of the named executive officers of Illinois Tool Works Inc. (the &#147;Company&#148;) as disclosed pursuant to
the compensation disclosure rules of the Securities and Exchange Commission under &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis,&#148; in the Summary Compensation Table, the related compensation tables and the related narrative disclosures in the
Company&#146;s proxy statement for its 2019 Annual Meeting, is hereby approved. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>The Board of Directors recommends a vote &#147;FOR&#148; the
approval of the compensation of </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>the Company&#146;s named executive officers. </B></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_36"></A>Proposal 4 -
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Binding</FONT> Stockholder Proposal to Permit </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Stockholders to Act by Written
Consent </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company has been notified that John Chevedden, whose address is 2215 Nelson Avenue, No.&nbsp;205, Redondo Beach, California 90278, intends to
present the following proposal (the &#147;Stockholder Proposal&#148;) for consideration at the 2019 Annual Meeting. Mr.&nbsp;Chevedden has submitted documentation indicating that he is the beneficial owner of no less than 100 shares of the
Company&#146;s common stock. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">You should read carefully the description of the proposal. The Board of Directors recommends that you vote &#147;AGAINST&#148; the
Stockholder Proposal. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Stockholder Proposal and Supporting Statement </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Proposal 4 &#150; Right to Act by Written Consent </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" COLOR="#00416a"><B>Resolved,</B></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL"> Shareholders request that our board of directors
undertake such steps as may be necessary to permit written consent by shareholders entitled to cast the minimum number of votes that would be necessary to authorize the action at a meeting at which all shareholders entitled to vote thereon were
present and voting. This written consent is to be consistent with applicable law and consistent with giving shareholders the fullest power to act by written consent consistent with applicable law. This includes shareholder ability to initiate any
topic for written consent consistent with applicable law. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Hundreds of major companies enable shareholder action by written consent. Taking
action by written consent in place of a meeting is a means shareholders can use to raise important matters outside the normal annual meeting cycle. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">This proposal topic won majority shareholder support at 13 major companies in a single year. This included 67%-support at both Allstate and Sprint.
Hundreds of major companies enable shareholder action by written consent. This proposal topic might have received a still higher vote than 67% at Allstate and Sprint if all shareholders had access to independent corporate governance advice. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If shareholders had a right to act by written consent, as called for in this proposal, shareholders would have a greater ability to engage our Board to
improve the qualifications of our directors and make sure that the Board of Directors is continually refreshed with new diverse talent in order to maintain director independence &#151; since a new director can be obtained by the use of written
consent. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">This proposal is important because Scott Santi was our CEO and was not overseen by an independent chairman. Mr.&nbsp;Santi received our
highest negative votes in 2018. Plus Lead Director James Skinner received our second highest negative votes and had long-tenure of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">13-years</FONT> (which can erode his independence). Susan Crown had long tenure of <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">24-years</FONT> (which can erode her independence) and was elevated to seats on 2 of our most important board committees. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">One option our company could take in response to this proposal would be to enable 10% of shares to call a special meeting since acting by written
consent and calling for a special shareholder meeting have some similarities. Some companies have improved the shareholder right to call a special meeting after receiving a shareholder proposal on the written consent topic </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Shareholder proposals such as this have played a leadership role in improving the governance rules of our company. As a result of shareholder proposals
an onerous 67% </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">62 </P>

</DIV></Center>

shareholder vote requirement was eliminated (2014), shareholders now have a right to call for a special meeting (2016)&nbsp;and there is now shareholder proxy access at our company (2016). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">Please vote yes: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Right to Act by Written Consent
&#151; Proposal 4 </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Board of Directors Statement in Opposition </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Our Board recommends a vote AGAINST this proposal. </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Board has carefully considered the Stockholder Proposal and recommends a vote AGAINST it. The Board believes that stockholder action by written consent is not
necessary, given ITW&#146;s current governance practices and structures, including stockholders&#146; existing ability to call a special meeting and the Company&#146;s strong stockholder engagement practices year-round. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Our Company has a track record of strong corporate governance. </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company is committed to sound corporate governance and has implemented numerous corporate governance policies and practices that ensure accountability of the Board

<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company continually evaluates stockholder feedback and developments in corporate governance, and we implement appropriate changes to our corporate governance
policies and practices when they appear to be in the best interests of the Company and our stockholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Action by written consent is
unnecessary because our stockholders already have the right to act outside of the annual meeting cycle. </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company has taken a number of steps to
enhance stockholder rights and provide stockholders with the ability to raise important matters outside of the annual meeting cycle. In particular, the Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> provide stockholders holding 20%
of the Company&#146;s shares with the right to call a special meeting, with no material restrictions. The Board continues to believe that our 20% threshold to call a special meeting is aligned with our stockholders&#146; interests because it is
designed to strike the </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">63 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
proper balance between enhancing stockholder rights and protecting against the risk that a small minority of stockholders, including those with special interests, could trigger the expense and
distraction of a special meeting to pursue matters that are not in the best interests of all of our stockholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company also regularly engages with its
stockholders regarding a variety of topics, including corporate governance, in order to stay informed of issues important to its stockholders. We invited holders of approximately 53% of our shares, represented by 26 investors, to engage with us
regarding this proposal, among other topics. Fourteen investors, holding in the aggregate 40% of our shares, accepted our invitation. A majority of these investors informed us that they do not support or are leaning against support for the granting
of written consent rights to stockholders, particularly when there is already a right to call special meetings, which our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> provide. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">These practices provide stockholders with meaningful, year-round opportunities to bring important matters to the attention of the Company, the Board and other
stockholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>A special meeting provides a deliberative forum for resolution of corporate matters and is therefore a more appropriate
method for stockholder action between annual meetings. </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board believes that a special meeting does far more to support stockholders&#146;
interests than action by written consent, because a special meeting ensures that all stockholders receive notice, adequate time to review proposals and a forum for expressing their views. By contrast, stockholder action by written consent may not
result in all stockholders receiving notice of a proposed action and does not permit a variety of views on a proposal to be exchanged. This means that action by written consent could deprive many stockholders of the critical opportunity to assess,
discuss, deliberate and vote on pending matters that may have important ramifications for both the Company and our stockholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In addition to disenfranchising
stockholders, action by written consent can create substantial confusion and disruption, as stockholder groups may solicit multiple written consents simultaneously, some of which may be duplicative or contradictory. This level of confusion can
impose significant administrative and financial burdens on the Company, while providing little or no corresponding benefit to stockholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In short, the Board
believes that matters of sufficient importance to warrant action between annual stockholder meetings should not be decided without notification to all stockholders, an opportunity for all stockholders to be heard and a vote at a duly convened
meeting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Our stockholders&#146; ability to call a special meeting is well within the mainstream for public companies.
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our current 20% threshold is below 25%, which is the most common threshold for special meeting rights at public companies and is equal to or lower
than the comparable threshold adopted by approximately 76% of the American companies in the S&amp;P 500 Index that permit stockholders to call a special meeting (which only 65% of such companies permit at all). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">A threshold as low as 10% could permit a small group of stockholders to use the extraordinary measure of calling a special meeting to serve the group&#146;s narrow
self-interests at the expense of the vast majority of the stockholders and the Company. This concern is heightened if such stockholders can borrow shares from other stockholders for the sole purpose of meeting the required threshold necessary to
call a special meeting. The Board believes that if fewer than 20% of the shares desire a special meeting, then the need for a special meeting has not been demonstrated and that a 20% threshold ensures that a meaningful percentage of our stockholders
agree on the need for a special meeting before it is called. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">64 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Conclusion </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Given the actions that the Company has taken to enhance stockholder rights and its commitment to strong corporate governance, and the existing right of stockholders to
call special meetings, the Board believes that adoption of this proposal would not advance the Company&#146;s or our stockholders&#146; interests. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>For the foregoing reasons, the Board of Directors believes that this proposal is not in </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>the best interests of the Company or our stockholders and unanimously recommends </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>that you vote &#147;AGAINST&#148; this proposal. </B></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">65 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom587187_37"></A>Proposal 5 -
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Binding</FONT> Stockholder Proposal to Set Company-Wide Greenhouse Gas Emissions Targets </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company has been
notified that Ellen Low Webster Trust, c/o Trillium Asset Management LLC, Walden Asset Management and Friends Fiduciary Corporation intend to present the following proposal for consideration at the 2019 Annual Meeting. The address and number of
shares of the Company&#146;s common stock held by the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">co-proponents</FONT> will be promptly provided upon oral or written request made to our Corporate Secretary. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">You should read carefully the description of the proposal. The Board of Directors recommends that you vote &#147;AGAINST&#148; this proposal. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Stockholder Proposal and Supporting Statement </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Resolved: </B>Shareholders request Illinois Tool Works, Inc. (ITW) adopt quantitative, company-wide targets for reducing greenhouse gas (GHG)
emissions, consistent with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement, and report annually, at reasonable cost and omitting proprietary information, on its plans and progress towards achieving these targets. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Supporting Statement: </B>Proponents recommend ITW consider the methods outlined by the Science Based Targets Initiative
(<U>sciencebasedtargets.org</U>) to ensure its emissions reductions targets are consistent with the ambitions of the Paris Climate Agreement. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Whereas: </B>Scientists expect that failure to mitigate climate change will lead to additional sea level rise, more extreme weather, mass migration,
and public health impacts from heat waves, fires, and changing disease vectors. To manage these risks, representatives from approximately 195 countries adopted the Paris Climate Agreement, which aims to limit the increase in global average
temperature &#151; and the most devastating societal impacts of climate change &#151; by reducing GHG emissions. Aligning corporate practices with this global goal is widely seen as a prudent course of action to help manage the associated
reputational, regulatory, and financial risks. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">While some of ITW&#146;s divisions have taken action to reduce emissions, ITW&#146;s company-wide
emissions intensity increased 9% from 2013 to 2017. Despite this increased emissions trajectory, ITW has not set emissions reduction targets or signaled an intent to align its strategies with the ambitions of the Paris Agreement. Setting GHG
reduction targets would enable shareholders to better evaluate emissions performance trends and the effectiveness of ITW&#146;s strategies. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">ITW has
set company-wide, quantitative goals for other aspects of its business. For example, ITW has a goal for 30% of its global leaders to be women by 2020. The Company has made progress towards this goal every year. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">ITW states its emissions intensity is below its peer average. However, this doesn&#146;t offset the fact that ITW&#146;s increased emissions set it
apart from its peers that have been steadily reducing emissions for years. According to proponent&#146;s research, 13 out of 17 of ITW&#146;s self-identified peers have set quantitative, company-wide emissions reduction targets. Four of these
businesses have committed to science-based targets thus far. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Notable examples include: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="11%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">3M &#151; Reduced absolute emissions 64% from 2002 to 2014 and aims to reduce GHG emissions 50% by 2025 while growing the
business; </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="11%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Johnson Controls &#151; reduced GHG emissions intensity 41% from 2002 to 2014 and targets an additional 15% reduction by
2020; </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">66 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="11%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Honeywell &#150; Set its third GHG emissions reduction goal after achieving its first two; reduced emissions intensity more
than 65% from 2004 to 2017. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Last year this proposal received a 24.6% vote. As an additional sign of growing investor interest,
one of the recommendations of The Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures, whose members include representatives from BlackRock, JPMorgan Chase, and UBS Asset Management is: &#147;Describe the targets used by the organization to manage
climate-related risks and opportunities and performance against these targets.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Our Board recommends a vote AGAINST this proposal.
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Board recognizes that part of ITW&#146;s commitment to operating responsibly is recognizing that our operations and footprint impact the environment.
ITW addresses environmental management through its decentralized operations, with ongoing support and guidance from the ITW management team and Board. After careful consideration, and for the reasons noted below, the Board has determined that the
above shareholder proposal is not in the best interests of ITW and its stockholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">First, ITW has a strong, demonstrated commitment to Corporate Social
Responsibility (CSR). We are committed to operating our business in a way that demonstrates our dedication to global environmental sustainability. We are also committed to transparency to our stockholders and stakeholders, and we have made and
continue to make a broad set of disclosures regarding environmental, social and governance matters. In 2009, we formally recognized this commitment with the establishment of our CSR initiative and the first release of our annual CSR report. Our
annual CSR reports are available on our website and continue to be enhanced each year. These reports contain detailed information regarding our ongoing commitment to CSR and related disclosures, including the meaningful percentage of overall revenue
related to clean-technology products. Moreover, for the last eleven years, ITW has participated in the Carbon Disclosure Project (CDP), an independent, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-profit</FONT> organization to which large global companies
report their emissions data. Notably, as of 2017, ITW&#146;s environmental data is third-party verified, and our CDP Climate Change and CDP Water reports are now posted on our website. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Second, the Board believes that ITW&#146;s management and Board are best positioned to structure, monitor and adjust ITW&#146;s sustainability efforts in the manner that
best serves the interests of the Company and all of ITW&#146;s stockholders and stakeholders. The Board has an active role in the review of the Company&#146;s overall strategies, is responsible for risk oversight of the Company, including with
respect to environmental, safety and health matters, and will periodically review the Company&#146;s CSR strategy and initiatives. Furthermore, the Board and management are dedicated to continuing to advance ITW&#146;s commitment to global
environmental sustainability, and they recognize the value in emissions disclosures and related environmental programs. The highly prescriptive nature of the shareholder proposal is not the best way for sustainability programs and related goals to
be achieved, particularly given the Company&#146;s demonstrated commitment to the CSR initiatives noted above. ITW&#146;s commitments to CSR are best accomplished through CSR strategies developed internally because management, with oversight by the
Board, is best positioned to determine how to drive sustainability within the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Third, ITW is a highly decentralized company and, therefore, believes that
specific sustainability goals and initiatives at ITW divisions are most effectively established and managed <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;bottom-up&#148;</FONT> at each of our divisions rather than &#147;top down&#148; from the corporate
center. Our CSR initiatives are designed to maintain a careful balance between our Board&#146;s and management&#146;s commitment to the environment and the flexibility required by our Company&#146;s structure. ITW&#146;s highly decentralized
structure is a critical element of ITW&#146;s differentiated business model, and this structure drives accountability and results. Our businesses are responsible for managing their own performance and implementing the most impactful opportunities
for their unique operations, and they thrive in our &#147;flexibility within the framework&#148; culture. Our businesses are clear about what is expected of them with respect to our </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">67 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
business model, strategy and core values. We believe our environmental commitment is strengthened by decentralization because it gives our businesses the flexibility to develop sustainable,
innovative approaches best suited for their unique operations. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Fourth, ITW already annually tracks and publishes significantly detailed environmental data,
including GHG emissions, energy usage, GHG emissions intensity indicators, total water withdrawn, sustainability and other relevant data. As our 2017 CSR report showed, ITW had year-over-year improvements in energy and emissions intensity, total
water withdrawn, water intensity and total recycled material. Our 2018 CSR report will publish our 2018 emissions data, and for the first time we expect to show year-over-year comparisons of third-party verified emissions data. The data for years
prior to 2017 does not allow for the most relevant comparative measurement due to the significant amount of divestiture and business structure simplification activities prior to 2017 as well as an acquisition in
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">mid-2016.</FONT> Moreover, our total GHG emissions and GHG emissions intensity are below the average of our peer group, and two of the companies mentioned by the proponents are the highest GHG emitters in our peer
group by a wide margin. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">One of the proponents of this proposal submitted a similar proposal in 2018 that received the support of only 24.6% of the shares voted.
Notably, a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">co-sponsor</FONT> of the 2018 proposal declined to join in the current proposal in order to give ITW additional time to develop its strategy regarding sustainability. Shareholder proposals similar to the
current proposal that were submitted to our peer companies during the past three proxy seasons did not pass. Moreover, we regularly engage with our stockholders regarding a variety of topics, including CSR. We invited holders of approximately 53% of
our shares, represented by 26 investors, to engage with us regarding this proposal, among other topics. Fourteen investors, holding in the aggregate 40% of our shares, accepted our invitation. A majority of these investors informed us that they
either do not support or are not inclined to support shareholder proposals that prescriptively require sustainability goals and targets, understanding that management and the Board should be responsible for determining company-appropriate
objectives. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In conclusion, we believe our stockholders should agree with ITW&#146;s approach to this important topic and place more confidence in a management team
and company that have consistently delivered on our commitments than on the imposition of a prescriptive, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">off-the-shelf</FONT></FONT> approach by a third party. The setting of the
Company&#146;s CSR strategy and goals is best accomplished by our own management, with Board oversight, in a manner that best serves the interests of the Company and all of ITW&#146;s stockholders and stakeholders. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>For the foregoing reasons, the Board of Directors believes that this proposal is not in </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>the best interests of the Company or our stockholders and unanimously recommends </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>that you vote &#147;AGAINST&#148; this proposal. </B></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">68 </P>

</DIV></Center>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Who may vote? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Stockholders at the close of business on March&nbsp;4, 2019, the record date, may vote. On that date, there were 326,918,516 shares of ITW common stock outstanding. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How many votes do I have? </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Each share of
ITW common stock that you own entitles you to one vote. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How do I vote? </I></B></FONT></P>
